The second allegation made by Springwell, based upon an alleged breach of fiduciary duty, reflects the issue set out at paragraph 43 of the List of Issues, namely that, in proposing Russian, former Soviet Union and Indonesian investments to Springwell in and after October 1997, CMB and CMIL (by JA) acted in breach of fiduciary duty: (i) by not acting in the best interests of Springwell but by acting in the interests of Chase; and (ii) by consciously taking advantage of AP’s lack of expertise, knowledge and resources to sell Springwell inappropriate investments. These allegations were pleaded in terms that Chase deliberately did not “control” JA’s dealings with Springwell because Springwell was a very profitable client;
RADC paragraphs 92(a). that Springwell was a “stuffee”, namely a client who could be stuffed with paper which nobody else would buy;
RADC paragraph 92(b). and that JA took advantage of AP when he knew or ought to have known that any fair presentation of the risks involved in purchasing Russian paper would lead him not to purchase it
RADC paragraph 182. .
